Description:
    Makes a Rails app a "native port hasher": its development server port is
    derived deterministically from the project's folder name (an MD5 hash into
    the band 3000..3999) instead of always being 3000. Any tool — or AI agent —
    can then find a project's dev server without guessing or scanning ports;
    it just recomputes the hash via bin/find_server_port.

    The generator:
      1. Ships bin/find_server_port — the resolver and single source of truth
         for port assignment. Reports the live recorded port if the server is
         already running; otherwise returns the hashed slot, walking forward
         only if another project already holds it.
      2. Wires bin/dev to boot on $(bin/find_server_port) and record the chosen
         port to tmp/pids/dev_server.port.
      3. For Foreman-based bin/dev launchers, adds foreman to the development
         bundle, removes the global gem install bootstrap, pins BUNDLE_GEMFILE
         to this app, and runs `bundle exec foreman`.
      4. Appends agent guidance to CLAUDE.md (don't assume 3000; resolve the port).

    It is idempotent and safe to run on a mature Rails app that already has its
    own bin/dev — it injects the PORT-resolution lines ahead of the existing
    launcher rather than replacing it.

Example:
    bin/rails generate hashed_ports

    This will:
      - Create bin/find_server_port (chmod 0755)
      - Inject PORT resolution into bin/dev
      - Normalize Foreman bin/dev launchers to run through Bundler
      - Append a "Dev Server Port" section to CLAUDE.md

After running standalone:
    bundle install              # needed if foreman was added to Gemfile

Resolve the port anytime:
    bin/find_server_port          # -> e.g. 3712
    bin/find_server_port --url    # -> http://localhost:3712
